This article discusses the executive orders issued by President Donald Trump on March 27, 2020, regarding healthcare in response to the COVID-19 pandemic. The orders were issued under the authority of the Defense Production Act of 1950 and the National Emergencies Act. The President declared a national emergency recognizing the threat posed by the novel coronavirus and the strain it could put on the healthcare system. The orders delegate authority to the Secretary of Health and Human Services and the Secretary of Homeland Security to prioritize and allocate health and medical resources, combat hoarding and price gouging, and expand domestic production of personal protective equipment and ventilators. The orders also authorize the making of voluntary agreements and plans of action by the private sector. The Secretaries are further delegated authority to implement the Act and determine nationwide priorities and allocation of resources. The Secretary of Homeland Security is authorized to control the distribution of materials in the civilian market. The Secretaries are required to consult with each other and periodically review the necessity of their designations. The article concludes by stating that implementing rules and regulations will be adopted, and the Assistant to the President for Trade and Manufacturing Policy will serve as National Defense Production Act Policy Coordinator. The general provisions state that the order does not impair existing authorities or functions and is subject to applicable law and appropriations. It also clarifies that the order does not create any enforceable rights or benefits against the United States or any other entity.